<li id="cite_note-27"><b><a href="#cite_ref-27" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="news">"Mark Twain is Dead at 74. End Comes Peacefully at His New England Home After a Long Illness.". New York Times. April 22, 1910.  "<a href="/wiki/Danbury,_Connecticut" title="Danbury, Connecticut">Danbury, Connecticut</a>, April 21, 1910. Samuel Langhorne Clemens, "Mark Twain," died at 22 minutes after 6 to-night. Beside him on the bed lay a beloved book -- it was Carlyle's " French Revolution" -- and near the book his glasses, pushed away with a weary sigh a few hours before. Too weak to speak clearly, "Give me my glasses," he had written on a piece of paper."</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Mark+Twain+is+Dead+at+74.+End+Comes+Peacefully+at+His+New+England+Home+After+a+Long+Illness.&amp;rft.atitle=&amp;rft.date=April+22%2C+1910&amp;rft.pub=New+York+Times&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Mark_Twain"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
